solution.p:
In , we showed that \sin\left(2\theta \right)=2\sin \theta \cos \theta. Since we know \sin \theta =\frac{1}{3}, we need to find \cos \theta . The identity \sin^2\left(\theta\right)+\cos^2\left(\theta\right)=1 allows us to find \cos \theta .  The value of \cos \theta  will be either positive or negative, depending on whether the endpoint of the arc \theta is in quadrant 1 or quadrant 2 of the unit circle.


     \cos \theta \amp =\pm \sqrt{1-\sin^2\left(\theta \right)}
     \cos \theta \amp =\pm \sqrt{1-\frac{1}{9}}=\pm \frac{2\sqrt{2}}{3}

    Therefore,\sin\left(2\theta \right)=2\sin \theta \cos \theta =2 \cdot \frac{1}{3} \cdot \left(\pm \frac{2\sqrt{2}}{3} \right)=\pm \frac{4\sqrt{2}}{9}.
